   =20
 =20

Statistically speaking, almost nobody who has ever bought Meta Platforms In=
c. stock bought it from Meta. Between its founding in 2004 and its 2012  in=
itial public offering, Facebook (as Meta was then called) raised about $2.9=
 billion by selling stock to venture capitalists.
  [1]
=C2=A0That IPO raised about $16 billion, though only about $6.8 billion=C2=
=A0went to Facebook; the rest went to early investors who sold their own st=
ock in the IPO. Facebook did  another stock offering a year later, raising =
another $1.5 billion for the company; it has never sold stock since then.
  [2]
 So over the last two decades,=C2=A0people have invested about $11.2 billio=
n in Meta by buying its stock.
That is a drop in the ocean compared to the amount of Meta stock that peopl=
e buy from each other on the stock exchange. People bought $9.5 billion of =
Meta stock=C2=A0yesterday. The day before, they=C2=A0bought about $11.2 bil=
lion of Meta stock: as much in one day as Meta sold in its whole history. L=
ast year=C2=A0about $1.6 trillion of Meta stock traded; the year before it =
was=C2=A0only a little less. In the entire history of Meta, on the order of=
 0.1% of all the money spent to buy Meta stock went to Meta; in the last ni=
ne years, the percentage is exactly 0%.
It is conventional to say that if you buy a share of Meta stock, which clos=
ed yesterday at $313.41, you are =E2=80=9Cinvesting in Meta.=E2=80=9D But w=
hat does that mean? It does not mean that you are giving $313 to Meta to us=
e to buy computers or pay workers; your $313 does not go to Meta at all, bu=
t to whoever else had the share of stock before you did. It does not mean t=
hat you get a check for your share of Meta=E2=80=99s profits: Meta has enor=
mous profits and has never paid a dividend. (Meta does do stock buybacks, i=
n which it voluntarily buys back shares from time to time, but I suppose it=
 could just as well buy Apple Inc. shares; nothing about Meta=E2=80=99s pro=
pensity to buy Meta shares seems to make those shares an =E2=80=9Cinvestmen=
t in=E2=80=9D Meta.)=C2=A0It does not mean that you get a say in the manage=
ment of Meta: Mark Zuckerberg owns super-voting shares and can make all the=
 decisions himself. It=C2=A0does=C2=A0mean that if someone acquires Meta in=
 a merger, you will get your proportionate share of the merger price, but M=
eta is an $800 billion company so that seems unlikely.
  [3]

And yet buying a share of Meta stock does seem, practically speaking, to be=
 a way to bet on Meta=E2=80=99s success. The stock goes up when Meta has go=
od news and down when it has bad news; the stock does=C2=A0behave like=C2=
=A0an investment in Meta. And I think that that is not   pure wishful think=
ing or confusion on the part of the stock market; there are norms and fiduc=
iary duties=C2=A0and expectations that, for instance, if Meta makes a ton o=
f cash and has no business need for it, it will spend the cash on buying ba=
ck stock, and will=C2=A0not=C2=A0spend it on=C2=A0building giant glass hous=
es for Mark Zuckerberg or whatever. The company has certain obligations to =
its shareholders, and though those obligations are not exactly =E2=80=9Csha=
re the profits with the shareholders,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0that is sort of how the=
 market interprets them.
Also,=C2=A0Meta=C2=A0did=C2=A0sell stock. Ages ago, and not very much of it=
 compared to the current trading volume, but it did. And part of the=C2=A0d=
eal, when it sold that stock, was that the buyers would eventually be able =
to resell it.
  [4]
=C2=A0The deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0not spelled out, but the background to all st=
ock offerings like this =E2=80=94=C2=A0was =E2=80=9Cgive us money today, an=
d we=E2=80=99ll give you some stock, and if all goes well the stock will go=
 up 100x and you will be able to resell it on the stock exchange to someone=
 else for billions of dollars.=E2=80=9D If you buy Meta stock today, you mi=
ght be buying it from someone who bought it from Meta all those years ago, =
and who is now cashing out. Probably not. But you are certainly buying it f=
rom someone who bought it from someone who bought it from someone who bough=
t it from =E2=80=A6=C2=A0etc. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0someone who bought it from Met=
a all those years ago.
  [5]
=C2=A0All the stock came from Meta, originally. You are not giving Meta any=
 money, today, when you buy Meta stock. But by a sort of financial backward=
 induction, you are=C2=A0making it possible for someone to have given Meta =
money years ago. If you and people like you weren=E2=80=99t around to buy M=
eta stock in 2023, nobody would have bought Meta stock in 2008.
In the US, there are securities laws that apply to Meta and other companies=
 that issue stock to the public. They generally have to=C2=A0register=C2=A0=
their sales of stock, filing a registration statement with the US Securitie=
s and Exchange Commission with details about their business and finances. T=
hey generally have to file annual and quarterly financial reports with the =
SEC so that the public can get updates on their financial results. If they =
lie in those reports, they can be sued for securities fraud. You can avoid =
many of these requirements (though not the fraud ones) by=C2=A0not=C2=A0iss=
uing stock to the public, by only selling it to rich people and institution=
al investors rather than letting everyone buy your stock: The securities la=
ws are mostly to protect public retail investors, and there are fewer discl=
osure requirements for sales to sophisticated institutional investors.
The simple story for why those rules exist is that in, like, the 1920s, a l=
ot of people started very shady companies and raised a lot of money by sell=
ing stock with bad and misleading disclosures. And so the securities laws w=
ere created to say =E2=80=9Cno, if you want to sell stock, you have to do t=
his disclosure, so people can know what they are buying and sue you if you =
lie.=E2=80=9D
  [6]
=C2=A0
That story does not really=C2=A0apply=C2=A0to Meta Platforms in 2023. Meta =
has not sold stock in ages. =E2=80=9CWe are not asking anyone to give us mo=
ney for our stock,=E2=80=9D you could almost imagine Meta saying, =E2=80=9C=
and it just trades on an exchange totally disconnected from us. Why should =
we have to file all of these reports and get sued for all our misstatements=
