=80=9D and reasoning by analogy.=C2=A0I think that this is, broadly speakin=
g, the right intuition, and I kind of wish it was the law, but I don=E2=80=
=99t really think it is. (And, again, it breaks down for tokens that have u=
tility in a blockchain ecosystem, which can start out looking like stock an=
d end up looking like airline miles or Starbucks gift cards or a currency t=
o pay for cloud computing time.)=09Judge Torres is right, the SEC is wrong,=
 and no crypto token is a security unless the issuer sells it directly to v=
enture capitalists in a=C2=A0fundraising round.

In some ways, that last result would be very good for the crypto industry. =
Most immediately, it would be a complete win for Coinbase Global Inc., whic=
h is   fighting its own case in which the SEC argues that it is operating a=
n unregistered securities exchange. One implication of Judge Torres=E2=80=
=99=C2=A0ruling is that cryptocurrencies are only securities if you know th=
at you are buying=C2=A0them directly from the company; if you buy them in t=
he secondary market =E2=80=94=C2=A0on Coinbase, for instance =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then they are not. So there are no securities listed on Coinbase =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0in fact, it is impossible=C2=A0for Coinbase to list any securities
  [11]
 =E2=80=94 so it is not an illegal securities exchange.   Good news for Coi=
nbase:

Coinbase Global Inc. rose the most since its public debut, climbing as high=
 as $109.21. The exchange is embroiled in a lawsuit of its own with the SEC=
 that alleges that it sold tokens that are unregistered securities.
=E2=80=9CThis underscores that direct sales of digital assets by an issuer =
will often be securities, but other sales, most notably sales on the second=
ary market, are unlikely to be deemed securities, which is a key argument i=
n Coinbase=E2=80=99s defense against the SEC,=E2=80=9D said Elliott Stein, =
Bloomberg Intelligence senior analyst for litigation.

More broadly, if you take this decision seriously, it means that the SEC ha=
s essentially no jurisdiction over crypto. Most token sales will either be =
(1) direct to institutional investors or (2) on exchanges. Sales on exchang=
es, says Judge Torres, are not securities offerings, because the buyer does=
n=E2=80=99t know=C2=A0that she is giving money to the issuer. Sales to inst=
itutional investors are=C2=A0securities offerings, but anyone selling anyth=
ing to institutional investors in 2023 can do so under an exemption from se=
curities registration. (Securities registration is only for=C2=A0public=C2=
=A0sales, not sales to big institutions.) So basically no crypto sales will=
 ever require SEC registration, no crypto exchange or brokerage will be a s=
ecurities=C2=A0exchange or brokerage,
  [12]
 and the SEC is out of crypto entirely.
But I am not sure that it is actually all that good for crypto in the long =
run. The message of this decision is that crypto companies can freely sell =
tokens to retail investors as long as those retail investors are uninformed=
 and the companies are secretive about it; only if they sell tokens openly =
to sophisticated investors will they get in trouble.=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s ba=
d.
In the 1920s,=C2=A0a lot of people started very shady companies and raised =
a lot of money by selling stock with bad and misleading disclosures, and so=
 the securities laws were created to stop them. That did not have the resul=
t of stamping out stock issuance in the US. Quite the contrary! The US stoc=
k market was=C2=A0helped enormously=C2=A0by having disclosure rules and pro=
tections for retail investors. The basic rule of the US stock market is =E2=
=80=9Cyou can kind of do what you like with sophisticated investors, but th=
ere are strict rules about how much you have to disclose to retail investor=
s,=E2=80=9D and that works out well. The opposite rule in this case =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou can do what you like with retail, but stay away from =
sophisticated investors=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems likely to work out po=
orly. If the law encourages=C2=A0crypto companies to take advantage of the =
least sophisticated investors, then who would want to invest in crypto?

