<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note: </strong><em>Money S=
tuff was supposed to be off today, but is not.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Ripple</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Statistically speaking, almost nobody who has =
ever bought Meta Platforms Inc. stock bought it from Meta. Between its foun=
ding in 2004 and its 2012 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/32082673.275409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXR=
hLzEzMjY4MDEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTEyMjQwMTExL2QyODc5NTRkNDI0YjQuaHRtI3RvYzI4Nzk1NF=
82/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcd5bd3e6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> initial public offering</a>,=
 Facebook (as Meta was then called) raised about $2.9 billion by selling st=
ock to venture capitalists.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0That IPO raised about $16 billion, though only about $6.8 billion=
=C2=A0went to Facebook; the rest went to early investors who sold their own=
 stock in the IPO. Facebook did <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/32082673.275409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhc=
i9kYXRhLzEzMjY4MDEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTEzNDgyOTUxL2Q2NDY2NTNkNDI0YjUuaHRt/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBac7b193f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> another stock offering</a> a year late=
r, raising another $1.5 billion for the company; it has never sold stock si=
nce then.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> So over the last two decades,=C2=A0people have invested about $11.2 bi=
llion in Meta by buying its stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is a drop in the ocean compared to the am=
ount of Meta stock that people buy from each other on the stock exchange. P=
eople bought $9.5 billion of Meta stock=C2=A0<em>yesterday</em>. The day be=
fore, they=C2=A0bought about $11.2 billion of Meta stock: as much in one da=
y as Meta sold in its whole history. Last year=C2=A0about $1.6 trillion of =
Meta stock traded; the year before it was=C2=A0only a little less. In the e=
ntire history of Meta, on the order of 0.1% of all the money spent to buy M=
eta stock went to Meta; in the last nine years, the percentage is exactly 0=
%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is conventional to say that if you buy a sh=
are of Meta stock, which closed yesterday at $313.41, you are =E2=80=9Cinve=
sting in Meta.=E2=80=9D But what does that mean? It does not mean that you =
are giving $313 to Meta to use to buy computers or pay workers; your $313 d=
oes not go to Meta at all, but to whoever else had the share of stock befor=
e you did. It does not mean that you get a check for your share of Meta=E2=
=80=99s profits: Meta has enormous profits and has never paid a dividend. (=
Meta does do stock buybacks, in which it voluntarily buys back shares from =
time to time, but I suppose it could just as well buy Apple Inc. shares; no=
thing about Meta=E2=80=99s propensity to buy Meta shares seems to make thos=
e shares an =E2=80=9Cinvestment in=E2=80=9D Meta.)=C2=A0It does not mean th=
at you get a say in the management of Meta: Mark Zuckerberg owns super-voti=
ng shares and can make all the decisions himself. It=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</e=
m>mean that if someone acquires Meta in a merger, you will get your proport=
ionate share of the merger price, but Meta is an $800 billion company so th=
at seems unlikely.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And yet buying a share of Meta stock does seem=
, practically speaking, to be a way to bet on Meta=E2=80=99s success. The s=
tock goes up when Meta has good news and down when it has bad news; the sto=
ck does=C2=A0<em>behave like=C2=A0</em>an investment in Meta. And I think t=
hat that is not <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32=
082673.275409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
TgtMDctMTEvaW52ZXN0b3JzLWdhdmUtc25hcC1hLWdpZnQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDcxNDIzX01PTkVZ=
