ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> her op=
inion</a>. Basically she ruled that=C2=A0<em>sometimes=C2=A0</em>XRP is a s=
ecurity and=C2=A0<em>sometimes=C2=A0</em>it isn=E2=80=99t. When Ripple sold=
 XRP to institutional investors in over-the-counter trades, with due dilige=
nce and investment agreements, that was an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=
=80=9D and so a securities offering. When Ripple sold XRP to retail investo=
rs in on-exchange trades, anonymously and with no disclosure, that was not =
an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=80=9D and so not a securities offering.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/32082673.275409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlb=
nQvY2RjMjA0MzUtZmYzZS00MTQ4LTk2YjctODFmNzAyMTFjYzJk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBa264d897" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> so weird</a>!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I should say: I don=E2=80=99t have a strong vi=
ew on whether XRP is a security. My gut is that it is, that it is effective=
ly a kind of quasi-stock in Ripple=E2=80=99s ecosystem, that it is valuable=
 if Ripple does the work to find banking partners and build a good payments=
 network and useless if it does not. Here, from Judge Torres=E2=80=99=C2=A0=
opinion, is the argument that XRP is a security, that it is an =E2=80=9Cinv=
estment contract=E2=80=9D because it =E2=80=9Cinvolves an investment of mon=
ey in a common enterprise with profits to come solely from the efforts of o=
thers=E2=80=9D (citations omitted):</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, the Institutional Buyers invested money =
by providing fiat or other currency in exchange for XRP.=C2=A0Defendants do=
 not dispute that Ripple received money for XRP through its Institutional S=
ales. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Each Institutional Buyer=E2=80=99s ability to =
profit was tied to Ripple=E2=80=99s fortunes and the fortunes of other Inst=
itutional Buyers because all Institutional Buyers received the same fungibl=
e XRP.=C2=A0Ripple used the funds it received from its Institutional Sales =
to promote and increase the value of XRP by developing uses for XRP and pro=
tecting the XRP trading market. When the value of XRP rose, all Institution=
al Buyers profited in proportion to their XRP holdings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Based on the totality of circumstances, the Co=
urt finds that reasonable investors, situated in the position of the Instit=
utional Buyers, would have purchased XRP with the expectation that they wou=
ld derive profits from Ripple=E2=80=99s efforts. From Ripple=E2=80=99s comm=
unications, marketing campaign, and the nature of the Institutional Sales, =
reasonable investors would understand that Ripple would use the capital rec=
eived from its Institutional Sales to improve the market for XRP and develo=
p uses for the XRP Ledger, thereby increasing the value of XRP.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Starting in 2013, Ripple marketed XRP to poten=
tial investors, including the Institutional Buyers, by distributing promoti=
onal brochures that touted XRP as an investment tied to the company=E2=80=
=99s success. For instance, in the =E2=80=9CDeep Dive=E2=80=9D brochure, wh=
ich was circulated to prospective investors, Ripple explains that its =E2=
=80=9Cbusiness model is predicated on a belief that demand for XRP will inc=
rease . . . if the Ripple protocol becomes widely adopted,=E2=80=9D and =E2=
=80=9C[i]f the Ripple protocol becomes the backbone of global value transfe=
r, Ripple . . . expects the demand for XRP to be considerable.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=A6 In February 2018, Schwartz posted on Reddit that what =E2=80=9Creall=
y set[s] XRP apart from any other digital asset=E2=80=9D is the =E2=80=9Cam=
azing team of dedicated professionals that Ripple has managed to amass to d=
evelop an ecosystem around XRP.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ripple raised money by selling XRP to investor=
s, it used the money to try to build its payments network, and it told the =
investors that if it successfully built its payments network then the value=
 of XRP would go up. That seems very securities-offering-like.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still I=C2=A0think that there is a real argume=
nt that XRP=C2=A0is not a security, that it is what crypto people call a =
=E2=80=9Cutility token,=E2=80=9D or a commodity like Bitcoin. XRP comes fro=
m the fairly early days of crypto, and it seems to have originally been con=
ceived as a Bitcoin competitor, a pure payment token. (In 2013,=C2=A0Ripple=
=E2=80=99s marketing materials said =E2=80=9CCan a virtual currency really =
create and hold value?=C2=A0<em>Bitcoin proves it can.</em>=E2=80=9D) You c=
an imagine saying something like =E2=80=9Cwell the XRP Ledger is just this =
decentralized blockchain that kind of exists on its own, and anyone can wor=
k on it and use it to transfer value, and the XRP tokens are just the curre=
ncy of that blockchain, like Bitcoin is the currency of the Bitcoin ledger.=
 XRP, like Bitcoins,=C2=A0are not securities, and it=C2=A0<em>just so happe=
ns=C2=A0</em>that Ripple Labs owns almost all of them, but it can sell them=
 freely just like any Bitcoin billionaire can sell her Bitcoins.=E2=80=9D I=
 don=E2=80=99t really think that that=E2=80=99s right, but I wasn=E2=80=99t=
 paying that much attention in 2013, and I think it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>poss=
ible</em>. =E2=80=9CXRP is just a commodity that Ripple owns a lot of, just=
 like oil is a commodity that Saudi Aramco owns a lot of, and oil is not a =
security.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Judge Torres seems to have (implicitly) re=
jected that argument and found that when Ripple went around selling XRP to =
institutional investors, it was selling securities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then she went on to say that when Ripple w=
ent around selling XRP on crypto exchanges with=C2=A0<em>no=C2=A0</em>discl=
osure, it was=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>selling securities. The disclosure cre=
ates the liability: If you go to an investor and say =E2=80=9Chi, we are th=
e issuer of this token, we think it is a good token, would you like some,=
=E2=80=9D then you are selling a security; if you just anonymously dump the=
 token to retail investors on a crypto exchange, then you are not. Judge To=
rres writes (citations omitted):</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Court next addresses Ripple=E2=80=99s Prog=
rammatic Sales, which occurred under different circumstances from the Insti=
tutional Sales. The SEC alleges that in the Programmatic Sales to public bu=
yers (=E2=80=9CProgrammatic Buyers=E2=80=9D) on digital asset exchanges, =
=E2=80=9CRipple understood that people were speculating on XRP as an invest=
ment,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cexplicitly targeted speculators[,] and made increas=
ed speculative volume a =E2=80=98target goal.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Having considered the economic reality of the =
Programmatic Sales, the Court concludes that the undisputed record does not=
 establish the third Howey prong. Whereas the Institutional Buyers reasonab=
ly expected that Ripple would use the capital it received from its sales to=
 improve the XRP ecosystem and thereby increase the price of XRP,=C2=A0Prog=
rammatic Buyers could not reasonably expect the same. Indeed, Ripple=E2=80=
=99s Programmatic Sales were blind bid/ask transactions, and Programmatic B=
uyers could not have known if their payments of money went to Ripple, or an=
y other seller of XRP. Since 2017, Ripple=E2=80=99s Programmatic Sales repr=
esented less than 1% of the global XRP trading volume. Therefore, the vast =
majority of individuals who purchased XRP from digital asset exchanges did =
not invest their money in Ripple at all. An Institutional Buyer knowingly p=
urchased XRP directly from Ripple pursuant to a contract, but the economic =
reality is that a Programmatic Buyer stood in the same shoes as a secondary=
 market purchaser who did not know to whom or what it was paying its money.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Further, it is not enough for the SEC to argue=
 that Ripple =E2=80=9Cexplicitly targeted speculators=E2=80=9D or that =E2=
=80=9CRipple understood that people were speculating on XRP as an investmen=
t.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=C2=A0It may certainly be the case that many Programma=
tic Buyers purchased XRP with an expectation of profit, but they did not de=
rive that expectation from Ripple=E2=80=99s efforts (as opposed to other fa=
ctors, such as general cryptocurrency market trends)=E2=80=94particularly b=
ecause none of the Programmatic Buyers were aware that they were buying XRP=
 from Ripple.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again: If you buy Meta stock on the stock exch=
ange, there is a 0% chance that you are buying it from Meta, or that Meta w=
ill get your $313 and use it to improve the Threads=C2=A0ecosystem and ther=
eby increase the price of Meta stock. And yet it is a security. What makes =
it a security is not that you have entered into a direct transaction with M=
eta, but that it was=C2=A0<em>originally issued=C2=A0</em>to raise money fo=
r Meta. It keeps being a security even as it trades.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now I should say that there is a popular argum=
ent in crypto circles that this is not true for =E2=80=9Cinvestment contrac=
ts,=E2=80=9D that an investment contract is only an investment contract whe=
n you buy it from the issuer, and that when it trades in the secondary mark=
et it is no longer a security.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote=
-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impo=
rtant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32082673=
.275409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDY=
tMDcvd2hlbi1pcy1hLXRva2VuLW5vdC1hLXNlY3VyaXR5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MTQyM19NT05FWV=
NUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzM=
DcxNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf6e961b1" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">This argument</a> is, for instance, very important to Coinbase Global=
 Inc., which is being sued by the SEC for operating an unregistered securit=
ies <em>exchange:=C2=A0</em>If crypto tokens are never securities in the se=
condary market, then Coinbase is off the hook.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But notice that Judge Torres goes=C2=A0<em>way=
=C2=A0</em>beyond that claim: She seems to conclude=C2=A0not only that seco=
ndary-market transactions are <em>never=C2=A0</em>securities offerings, bec=
ause the money doesn=E2=80=99t go to Ripple, but also that=C2=A0<em>even wh=
en the money does go to Ripple it=E2=80=99s not a securities offering</em>,=
 as long as Ripple=E2=80=99s sales are mixed in with enough secondary sales=
 that people don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>know=C2=A0</em>that their money is goin=
g to Ripple. Imagine if that were the law for stock offerings! (It is not: =
Public companies do =E2=80=9Cat-the-market=E2=80=9D offerings where they se=
ll stock anonymously on the stock exchange, but they have to register them =
and announce them publicly.) The implication is that if a crypto issuer pub=
licly and openly sells its tokens, that is an illegal securities offering, =
but if it sneaks in a few token sales on the exchange then it is not.<a cla=
ss=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">She goes on (citations omitted):</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It may certainly be the case that many Program=
matic Buyers purchased XRP with an expectation of profit, but they did not =
derive that expectation from Ripple=E2=80=99s efforts (as opposed to other =
factors, such as general cryptocurrency market trends)=E2=80=94particularly=
 because none of the Programmatic Buyers were aware that they were buying X=
RP from Ripple. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Institutional Buyers were sophisticated en=
tities, including institutional investors and hedge funds. An =E2=80=9Cexam=
ination of the entirety of the parties=E2=80=99 understandings and expectat=
ions,=E2=80=9D including the =E2=80=9Cfull set of contracts, expectations, =
and understandings centered on the sales and distribution of=E2=80=9D XRP s=
upports the conclusion that a reasonable investor, situated in the position=
 of the Institutional Buyers, would have been aware of Ripple=E2=80=99s mar=
keting campaign and public statements connecting XRP=E2=80=99s price to its=
 own efforts. There is no evidence that a reasonable Programmatic Buyer, wh=
o was generally less sophisticated as an investor, shared similar =E2=80=9C=
understandings and expectations=E2=80=9D and could parse through the multip=
le documents and statements that the SEC highlights, which include statemen=
ts (sometimes inconsistent) across many social media platforms and news sit=
es from a variety of Ripple speakers (with different levels of authority) o=
ver an extended eight-year period.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is: If you go around making public statem=
ents, on your website and on Reddit and elsewhere, saying things like =E2=
=80=9Cif you buy our token we will use the money to build an ecosystem and =
make the token more valuable,=E2=80=9D that makes your token a security,=C2=
=A0<em>but only to people who are sophisticated enough to read your website=
</em>. Sophisticated institutional investors who read your disclosure docum=
ents and understand that they are making an investment in your business are=
 entitled to the protections of the securities laws, while random retail da=
y-traders who just like your ticker symbol are not.=C2=A0<em>You cannot be =
doing securities fraud on them, because they are not paying attention</em>.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to say three things about that theory. =
First, it is actually intuitively very plausible? =E2=80=9CIf investors did=
n't read your advertising, then it doesn=E2=80=99t matter if those advertis=
ements were lies.=E2=80=9D Traditionally an element of fraud is =E2=80=9Cre=
liance=E2=80=9D: If you lie to people to get them to give you money, and th=
ey give you the money because of the lies, then you have defrauded them; if=
 they didn=E2=80=99t listen to you and were going to give you the money no =
matter what then maybe you haven=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, it is very much=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em=
>the rule of the stock market. It is absolutely the case that many retail i=
nvestors=C2=A0buying Meta stock have never looked at any of Meta=E2=80=99s =
SEC filings. If it turned out that Meta=C2=A0was=C2=A0<em>lying=C2=A0</em>i=
n those filings, and shareholders brought a securities-fraud class action, =
you could imagine Meta saying =E2=80=9Cwell, half of these plaintiffs didn=
=E2=80=99t read the filings, so you should throw the case out.=E2=80=9D But=
 that wouldn=E2=80=99t work! It is very standard US securities law that if =
you lie in your securities filings, all your shareholders can sue you, beca=
use=C2=A0<em>somebody=C2=A0</em>read the filings, and the lies affected the=
 stock price, and everyone who bought the stock at the (wrong, higher, infl=
ated-by-your-lies) price was defrauded. (This is called =E2=80=9C<a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32082673.275409/aHR0cHM6Ly9l=
bi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvRnJhdWRfb25fdGhlX21hcmtldA/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB860e2cad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">fraud on the market</a>=E2=80=9D: Each individual in=
vestor=C2=A0may not have relied on the lies, but the market did.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Third, it is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0obviously =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0terrible =E2=80=A6=C2=A0policy? =E2=80=9CThe securities laws prote=
ct only sophisticated investors who negotiate directly with the company, no=
t retail investors who trade on public exchanges=E2=80=9D is the exact oppo=
site of the normal rule. At the Information, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/32082673.275409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlaW5mb3JtYXRp=
b24uY29tL2FydGljbGVzL2NvdXJ0LXJ1bGluZy13aWxsLWNyZWF0ZS1yaXBwbGVzLWZvci1pbmR=
pdmlkdWFsLWNyeXB0by1pbnZlc3RvcnM_dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1zZyZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJn=
V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1hcnRpY2xlX2VtYWlsJnV0bV9jb250ZW50PWFydGljbGUtMTA4NzUmcmM9M=
WJkaTVo/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB38191de9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Akash Pasricha writes</=
a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Securities laws were specifically designed to =
protect individual investors, based on the idea that they =E2=80=9Ccan=E2=
=80=99t fend for themselves,=E2=80=9D James Carlson, a New York University =
adjunct securities regulation professor, told me today. By the same token .=
.. =E2=80=9Cbig institutional investors don=E2=80=99t need the protections =
of the securities laws. =E2=80=A6 This effectively stands that philosophy o=
n its head,=E2=80=9D he said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The implications of this part of the ruling ar=
e worrisome. As Carlson said, =E2=80=9CThe potential for bucket shop or boi=
ler room fraud =E2=80=A6 is alarming.=E2=80=9D Carlson painted a scenario w=
here a crypto firm issues tokens to heavyweight institutional traders, who =
get detailed disclosures required by securities laws, but they then flip it=
 to individual traders, who don=E2=80=99t get those disclosures.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Except you don=E2=80=99t even need that. Why s=
ell tokens to institutional traders (with securities disclosures) so that t=
hey can flip to retail, when you can just sell to retail yourself with <em>=
no</em> disclosure? As long as you sell to retail investors on the exchange=
, you=E2=80=99re safe. <em>Even if you broadly advertise how good a job you=
 will do and how much profit those investors will make</em>, you are still =
not doing a securities offering! Because you are selling the tokens anonymo=
usly on the crypto exchange, so no one can prove who bought them from you, =
so no one can prove if any of the buyers=C2=A0<em>read=C2=A0</em>your adver=
tising. It is a get-out-of-securities-law-free ruling.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I assume the SEC will appeal.=C2=A0I suppose t=
here are three possibilities here:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Judge Torres is wrong, the SEC is rig=
ht, and a thing is an "investment contract=E2=80=9D based on its original s=
ubstance, even if it later trades in the secondary market. If Meta sells me=
 a share of stock and then I sell it to you, it remains a security; if Howe=
y sells me an orange-grove-management contract and I resell it to you, it r=
emains a security. I think that this is the right answer, though I am not c=
onfident in that. Particularly in crypto, where tokens have a non-security =
utility, there=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>a good argument that tokens can change=
 character over time, that they can start off as securities and end up as s=
omething else. We have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/32082673.275409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjMtMDYtMDcvd2hlbi1pcy1hLXRva2VuLW5vdC1hLXNlY3VyaXR5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3M=
TQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0=
bV90ZXJtPTIzMDcxNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Cf6e961b1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">  discussed that theory before</a>, but I will just note=
 that it is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>the theory of the Ripple opinion. The th=
eory here is much stranger: It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0that each individual token sa=
le is a securities offering=C2=A0if the investors are sophisticated and not=
 if they are not.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Judge Torres is =
right in her =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=80=9D analysis, but the Howey =
=E2=80=9Cinvestment contract=E2=80=9D test is not the right way to think ab=
out crypto. The right way to think about crypto tokens is that they are qua=
si-stocks in crypto projects, and so they are securities even upon resale, =
not because each resale meets the Howey test but because stock is always st=
ock. The right way to think about crypto tokens is not by parsing the Howey=
 elements for each transaction, but by saying =E2=80=9Cwell how does it wor=
k with stock?=E2=80=9D and reasoning by analogy.=C2=A0I think that this is,=
 broadly speaking, the right intuition, and I kind of wish it was the law, =
but I don=E2=80=99t really think it is. (And, again, it breaks down for tok=
ens that have utility in a blockchain ecosystem, which can start out lookin=
g like stock and end up looking like airline miles or Starbucks gift cards =
or a currency to pay for cloud computing time.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Judge Torres is right, the SEC is wrong, and no crypto token =
is a security unless the issuer sells it directly to venture capitalists in=
 a=C2=A0fundraising round.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some ways, that last result would be very g=
ood for the crypto industry. Most immediately, it would be a complete win f=
or Coinbase Global Inc., which is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/32082673.275409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMDYvdGhlLXNlYy1jb21lcy1mb3ItY3J5cHRvP2NtcGlkPUJCRD=
A3MTQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJ=
nV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDcxNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBc0044ef0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  fighting its own case</a> in which the SEC argues t=
hat it is operating an unregistered securities exchange. One implication of=
 Judge Torres=E2=80=99=C2=A0ruling is that cryptocurrencies are only securi=
ties if you know that you are buying=C2=A0them directly from the company; i=
f you buy them in the secondary market =E2=80=94=C2=A0on Coinbase, for inst=
ance =E2=80=94=C2=A0then they are not. So there are no securities listed on=
 Coinbase =E2=80=94=C2=A0in fact, it is <em>impossible=C2=A0</em>for Coinba=
se to list any securities<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-11" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
