nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">  Good news for Coinbase</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Coinbase Global Inc. rose the most since its p=
ublic debut, climbing as high as $109.21. The exchange is embroiled in a la=
wsuit of its own with the SEC that alleges that it sold tokens that are unr=
egistered securities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis underscores that direct sales of=
 digital assets by an issuer will often be securities, but other sales, mos=
t notably sales on the secondary market, are unlikely to be deemed securiti=
es, which is a key argument in Coinbase=E2=80=99s defense against the SEC,=
=E2=80=9D said Elliott Stein, Bloomberg Intelligence senior analyst for lit=
igation.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More broadly, if you take this decision seriou=
sly, it means that the SEC has essentially no jurisdiction over crypto. Mos=
t token sales will either be (1) direct to institutional investors or (2) o=
n exchanges. Sales on exchanges, says Judge Torres, are not securities offe=
rings, because the buyer doesn=E2=80=99t <em>know=C2=A0</em>that she is giv=
ing money <em>to the issuer</em>. Sales to institutional investors <em>are=
=C2=A0</em>securities offerings, but anyone selling anything to institution=
al investors in 2023 can do so under an exemption from securities registrat=
ion. (Securities registration is only for=C2=A0<em>public=C2=A0</em>sales, =
not sales to big institutions.) So basically no crypto sales will ever requ=
ire SEC registration, no crypto exchange or brokerage will be a <em>securit=
ies=C2=A0</em>exchange or brokerage,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-12" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: non=
e !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-blo=
ck;">
<span>[12]</span>
</a> and the SEC is out of crypto entirely.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I am not sure that it is actually all that=
 good for crypto in the long run. The message of this decision is that cryp=
to companies can freely sell tokens to retail investors as long as those re=
tail investors are uninformed and the companies are secretive about it; onl=
y if they sell tokens openly to sophisticated investors will they get in tr=
ouble.=C2=A0<em>That=E2=80=99s bad</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the 1920s,=C2=A0a lot of people started ver=
y shady companies and raised a lot of money by selling stock with bad and m=
isleading disclosures, and so the securities laws were created to stop them=
. That did not have the result of stamping out stock issuance in the US. Qu=
ite the contrary! The US stock market was=C2=A0<em>helped enormously=C2=A0<=
/em>by having disclosure rules and protections for retail investors. The ba=
sic rule of the US stock market is =E2=80=9Cyou can kind of do what you lik=
e with sophisticated investors, but there are strict rules about how much y=
ou have to disclose to retail investors,=E2=80=9D and that works out well. =
The opposite rule in this case =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyou can do what you =
like with retail, but stay away from sophisticated investors=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0seems likely to work out poorly. If the law <em>encourages=C2=
=A0</em>crypto companies to take advantage of the least sophisticated inves=
tors, then who would want to invest in crypto?</p>
